                    <msContents>
                        <summary>
                            Ibn Khātūn, the translator, was a student of Shaykh Bahāʾī and one of the scholars of his time.
                            He has been gaining knowledge in Shaykh Bahāʾī's lessons for years. When he arrived at the court of Sultan Quṭb Shāhī (died 1035 AH/1616),
                            of the Quṭb Shāhī dynasty of India, he was commissioned to translate a book from Arabic to Persian, as were other scholars of his time.
                            He therefore selected Shaykh Bahāʾī's Arbaʿīn for translation, a book containing 40 hadiths, and called it Tarjumah-'i Quṭb-i Shāhī upon completion.
                        </summary>
                        <msItem>
